1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:14,187
Television has made it possible for people around the world to share in many different experiences – sports, music shows, films, and more.

2
00:00:14,187 --> 00:00:21,186
Yet many people would find it difficult to name the inventor of the television.

3
00:00:21,186 --> 00:00:32,157
They might also be surprised to learn that the inventor came up with the idea when he was just fourteen years old.

4
00:00:32,157 --> 00:00:43,584
Today, we explore the life of one of the great inventors of 20th century America: Philo Taylor Farnsworth.

5
00:00:43,584 --> 00:00:54,089
Philo Farnsworth was born in August 1906, near Indian Creek in the western state of Utah.

6
00:00:54,089 --> 00:01:01,768
The house he lived in for the first few years of his life had no electricity.

7
00:01:01,768 --> 00:01:09,311
But Philo read about electricity and quickly began to experiment with it.

8
00:01:09,311 --> 00:01:19,411
One night, Philo read a magazine story about the idea of sending pictures and sound through the air.

9
00:01:19,411 --> 00:01:26,461
The story said some of the world’s best scientists were working on the idea.

10
00:01:26,461 --> 00:01:36,869
It said these scientists were using special machines to try to make a kind of device to send pictures.

11
00:01:36,869 --> 00:01:42,922
Fourteen-year-old Philo decided these famous scientists were wrong.

12
00:01:42,922 --> 00:01:47,968
He decided that mechanical devices would never work.

13
00:01:47,968 --> 00:01:53,886
Philo believed such a device would have to be electronic.

14
00:01:53,886 --> 00:01:59,492
Philo knew electrons could be made to move very fast.

15
00:01:59,492 --> 00:02:05,996
All he would have to do was find a way to make electrons do the work.

16
00:02:05,996 --> 00:02:10,567
Soon, Philo had an idea for such a receiver.

17
00:02:10,567 --> 00:02:17,890
It would trap light in a container and send the light on a line of electrons.

18
00:02:17,890 --> 00:02:22,056
Philo called it “light in a bottle.”

19
00:02:22,056 --> 00:02:30,513
Several days later, Philo told his teacher about a device that could capture pictures.

20
00:02:30,513 --> 00:02:35,920
He drew a plan for it and gave it to his teacher.

21
00:02:35,920 --> 00:02:39,436
Philo’s drawing seemed very simple.

22
00:02:39,436 --> 00:02:45,715
But it still clearly showed the information needed to build a television.

23
00:02:45,715 --> 00:02:49,559
Philo’s teacher was Justin Tolman.

24
00:02:49,559 --> 00:03:02,242
Many years later, Philo would credit Mr. Tolman with guiding his imagination and helping him open the doors of science.

25
00:03:02,242 --> 00:03:11,754
In September 1927, Philo turned on a device that was the first working television receiver.

26
00:03:11,754 --> 00:03:16,572
In another room was the first television camera.

27
00:03:16,572 --> 00:03:22,326
Philo had invented the special camera tube earlier that year.

28
00:03:22,326 --> 00:03:29,687
While the image produced on the receiver was not very clear, the device worked.

29
00:03:29,687 --> 00:03:38,756
Within a few months, Philo had found several people who wanted to invest money in his invention.

30
00:03:38,756 --> 00:03:46,789
In August 1930, the United States government gave Philo patent documents.

31
00:03:46,789 --> 00:03:54,244
These documents aimed to protect his invention from being copied by others.

32
00:03:54,244 --> 00:04:04,127
Still, he became involved in legal disputes with a powerful company at the time known as RCA.

33
00:04:04,127 --> 00:04:12,189
Philo won the disputes but faced many business and financial difficulties in his life.

34
00:04:12,189 --> 00:04:19,991
He developed more than 100 devices that helped make modern television possible.

35
00:04:19,991 --> 00:04:32,373
He also developed early radar, invented the first electronic microscope, and worked on developing peaceful uses of atomic energy.

36
00:00:00,000 --> 00:04:37,724
Philo Farnsworth died in March of 1971.

37
00:04:37,724 --> 00:04:44,701
He is considered one of the most important inventors of the 20th century.

38
00:04:44,701 --> 00:04:47,483
I’m John Russell.